Steps to Launch:
Go to AWS Console > EC2 > Launch Instance.
Choose AMI:
Linux: Amazon Linux 2 (e.g., for a web server).
Windows: Windows Server 2019 (e.g., for a .NET app).
Select instance type (e.g., t2.micro for a small blog site).
Configure: Place in a VPC/subnet (e.g., public subnet for web access).
Add storage (e.g., 8GB for Linux, 30GB for Windows).
Add tags (e.g., Name: MyWebServer).
Security Group: Allow port 22 (SSH) for Linux, 3389 (RDP) for Windows.
Launch with a key pair (e.g., my-key.pem).
Connect:
Linux: ssh -i my-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip> (e.g., access a Linux server to install Apache).
Windows: Use RDP client with .pem key (e.g., manage a Windows server hosting a corporate app).
Real-World Example: A startup launches a Linux EC2 instance to host a WordPress site and a Windows EC2 instance for an internal HR tool.
